{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UKWSEpAPRCtzdaQDvV1E7N","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_016sgmdebjgTnwUQy3JNY1ho","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/plan.md","content":"# RabbitMQ Change/Migration Plan\n\n**Prepared:** 2026-06-26\n**Namespace:** `karma-rabbitmq-change-plan-only-20260-ce35f655`\n**Author:** Operations Team (planning only — no changes applied)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Current State Snapshot\n\n### Cluster\n\n| Property | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Nodes | 3 (all disk nodes: rabbitmq-0, rabbitmq-1, rabbitmq-2) |\n| RabbitMQ version | **3.12.14** (release series marked **out of support**) |\n| Erlang/OTP version | 25.3.2.15 |\n| Container image | `rabbitmq:3.12-management` |\n| Cluster partition handling | `pause_minority` |\n| Queue master locator | `min-masters` |\n| Guest loopback | disabled (`loopback_users.guest = false`) |\n| Peer discovery | Kubernetes (`rabbit_peer_discovery_k8s`) |\n| AMQP listener | port 5672 |\n| Management API listener | port 15672 |\n| Alarms | none |\n| Network partitions | none |\n\n### Virtual Hosts\n\n| vhost | Notes |\n|---|---|\n| `/` | Default vhost |\n| `/app` | Application vhost |\n\n### Users and Permissions\n\n| User | Tags | `/` configure/write/read | `/app` configure/write/read |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `admin` | administrator | `.*` / `.*` / `.*` | `.*` / `.*` / `.*` |\n| `app-user` | *(none)* | *(no access)* | `.*` / `.*` / `.*` |\n\n### Policies\n\nNo policies are defined on either vhost (`/` or `/app`).\n\n### Queues\n\n| vhost | Name | Type | Durable | Arguments |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| `/app` | `app-queue` | classic | true | *(none)* |\n\nNo queues exist in the `/` vhost.\n\n### Exchanges (`/app` vhost)\n\nOnly built-in default exchanges are present (amq.direct, amq.topic, amq.fanout, amq.headers, amq.match, amq.rabbitmq.trace, default `\"\"`). No custom exchanges.\n\n### Enabled Plugins\n\n`rabbitmq_management`, `rabbitmq_management_agent`, `rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s`, `rabbitmq_peer_discovery_common`, `rabbitmq_web_dispatch`, `amqp_client`, `cowboy`, `cowlib`\n\n### Feature Flags (all enabled)\n\n`quorum_queue`, `stream_queue`, `classic_mirrored_queue_version`, `classic_queue_type_delivery_support`, `feature_flags_v2`, and all standard 3.12 flags.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Issues and Risks Identified\n\n### 2.1 Version Out of Support (Critical)\nRabbitMQ 3.12.x reached end-of-life. It no longer receives security patches or bug fixes. Upgrade is required.\n\n### 2.2 Classic Queue at Risk (High)\n`app-queue` is a **classic** durable queue. Classic mirrored queues were deprecated in 3.12 and are removed in 4.0. Even without an HA policy today, a future upgrade to 4.0 requires all classic queues to be migrated to **quorum queues** (the recommended HA queue type) or stream queues beforehand.\n\n### 2.3 No HA Policy on `app-queue` (Medium)\nThere are no policies defined in `/app`. `app-queue` has no replication; if the node that holds the queue master fails, the queue becomes unavailable until that node recovers. For production use a quorum queue or a HA policy is required.\n\n### 2.4 `queue_master_locator = min-masters` Deprecated (Low)\nThe `queue_master_locator` configuration key is deprecated in RabbitMQ 3.13+ and removed in 4.0. It must be replaced with the per-queue `x-queue-master-locator` argument or the new `queue_leader_locator` setting.\n\n### 2.5 `app-user` Has No Tags (Low)\n`app-user` has full access to `/app` but no management tags. If this user needs to access the management UI or monitoring APIs, the `monitoring` tag should be added. If it is a pure application service account, this is acceptable.\n\n### 2.6 Erlang/OTP 25 Compatibility Window (Informational)\nRabbitMQ 3.13 supports Erlang 25 and 26; 4.0 requires Erlang 26+. The container image must be updated to include a supported Erlang version when upgrading.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Upgrade and Migration Plan\n\n### Phase 0 — Pre-Change Checklist (before change window)\n\n- [ ] Confirm no active consumers or producers will be disrupted; coordinate with app teams.\n- [ ] Take a definition export backup:\n  ```\n  rabbitmqctl export_definitions /tmp/definitions-backup.json\n  ```\n  Copy the file out of the pod (`kubectl cp`).\n- [ ] Verify all 3 nodes are healthy (`rabbitmqctl cluster_status`); do not upgrade a degraded cluster.\n- [ ] Confirm PersistentVolumeClaims are bound and backed by a storage class that survives pod deletion.\n- [ ] Pin `imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent` and pre-pull the new image on all nodes if possible, to reduce rollout time.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 1 — Migrate `app-queue` from Classic to Quorum (no downtime)\n\n**Rationale:** Quorum queues are the supported HA queue type in 3.12+ and the only durable replicated type in 4.0. Classic queues must be migrated before upgrading to 4.0.\n\n**Steps (during change window, before the image upgrade):**\n\n1. Drain any messages currently in `app-queue` or ensure consumers are paused.\n2. Delete the classic queue:\n   ```\n   rabbitmqctl -p /app delete_queue app-queue\n   ```\n3. Re-declare as a quorum queue:\n   ```\n   rabbitmqctl -p /app declare_queue name=app-queue durable=true \\\n     arguments='{\"x-queue-type\":\"quorum\"}'\n   ```\n   Alternatively, use the Management HTTP API or have the application re-declare on startup with `x-queue-type: quorum` in its queue arguments.\n4. Verify the queue appears with `type=quorum`:\n   ```\n   rabbitmqctl list_queues -p /app name type durable\n   ```\n\n**Impact:** Brief queue downtime during delete/re-declare (~seconds). Coordinate with producers/consumers.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 2 — Add HA / Queue Policy (no downtime)\n\nAdd a policy to the `/app` vhost that enforces quorum queue defaults and sets a replication factor of 3 (matching the node count):\n\n```\nrabbitmqctl set_policy -p /app ha-quorum \".*\" \\\n  '{\"x-queue-type\":\"quorum\",\"x-quorum-initial-group-size\":3}' \\\n  --apply-to queues --priority 0\n```\n\nThis ensures any future queues declared in `/app` without explicit type arguments also become quorum queues.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 3 — Remove Deprecated `queue_master_locator` Config\n\nBefore or alongside the image upgrade, update `rabbitmq.conf` (the ConfigMap or Secret that supplies `/etc/rabbitmq/rabbitmq.conf`) to remove the deprecated directive:\n\n```diff\n-queue_master_locator = min-masters\n+queue_leader_locator = balanced\n```\n\n`queue_leader_locator = balanced` is the 3.13+/4.0 equivalent and achieves the same distribution goal.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 4 — Upgrade RabbitMQ 3.12 → 3.13 (rolling, one node at a time)\n\n**Target image:** `rabbitmq:3.13-management` (latest 3.13.x patch)\n\nRabbitMQ supports single-version rolling upgrades. The cluster runs mixed versions during the rollout, which is safe.\n\n**Procedure:**\n\n1. Put `rabbitmq-2` into maintenance mode:\n   ```\n   rabbitmqctl -n rabbit@rabbitmq-2... enable_feature_flag all   # ensure 3.12 flags enabled\n   rabbitmqctl -n rabbit@rabbitmq-2... maintenance\n   ```\n2. Delete the `rabbitmq-2` pod (the StatefulSet will restart it with the new image after you patch the image):\n   ```\n   kubectl -n <ns> set image statefulset/rabbitmq rabbitmq=rabbitmq:3.13-management\n   kubectl -n <ns> rollout status statefulset/rabbitmq --timeout=10m\n   ```\n   The StatefulSet rollout strategy (`RollingUpdate` with `partition`) should be used to upgrade one pod at a time:\n   ```\n   kubectl -n <ns> patch statefulset rabbitmq -p '{\"spec\":{\"updateStrategy\":{\"rollingUpdate\":{\"partition\":2}}}}'\n   kubectl -n <ns> delete pod rabbitmq-2\n   # wait for rabbitmq-2 to rejoin, then partition=1, delete rabbitmq-1, then partition=0, delete rabbitmq-0\n   ```\n3. After each pod rejoins, verify:\n   ```\n   rabbitmqctl cluster_status\n   rabbitmqctl list_queues -p /app name type state\n   ```\n4. After all 3 nodes are on 3.13, enable any new feature flags:\n   ```\n   rabbitmqctl enable_feature_flag all\n   ```\n\n**Expected downtime:** None for queue traffic (quorum queue replicas remain on untouched nodes). Management UI briefly unavailable on the node being restarted.\n\n---\n\n### Phase 5 — Upgrade RabbitMQ 3.13 → 4.0 (rolling, one node at a time)\n\n**Target image:** `rabbitmq:4.0-management` (latest 4.0.x patch, requires Erlang 26+; verify image bundles Erlang 26)\n\n**Prerequisites before this phase:**\n- All queues must be quorum or stream type (Phase 1 complete).\n- `queue_master_locator` removed from config (Phase 3 complete).\n- All 3.13 feature flags enabled (Phase 4 complete).\n- No classic mirrored queue HA policies exist (currently confirmed none).\n\n**Procedure:** Identical rolling procedure as Phase 4 using `partition`-based rollout. After all nodes are on 4.0:\n```\nrabbitmqctl enable_feature_flag all\n```\n\n---\n\n### Phase 6 — Post-Upgrade Validation\n\n- [ ] `rabbitmqctl cluster_status` — all 3 nodes running, no alarms, no partitions.\n- [ ] `rabbitmqctl list_queues -p /app name type state members` — `app-queue` is type `quorum`, state `running`, 3 members.\n- [ ] `rabbitmqctl list_users` — `admin` and `app-user` present with correct tags.\n- [ ] `rabbitmqctl list_permissions -p /app` — permissions unchanged.\n- [ ] Management UI accessible at port 15672.\n- [ ] Application can publish to and consume from `app-queue` in `/app` vhost.\n- [ ] Run definition export and compare against pre-change backup.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Optional Hardening Recommendations\n\n| Recommendation | Priority | Effort |\n|---|---|---|\n| Add `monitoring` tag to `app-user` if it needs management API access | Low | Minutes |\n| Restrict `app-user` permissions to specific resources rather than `.*` (principle of least privilege) | Medium | Minutes |\n| Set `cluster_partition_handling = autoheal` if `pause_minority` causes availability issues during node restarts | Low | Config change |\n| Enable `rabbitmq_prometheus` plugin for Prometheus/Grafana metrics scraping | Medium | Minutes |\n| Configure resource limits on the StatefulSet containers (currently `resources: {}`) | Medium | YAML change |\n| Set `vm_memory_high_watermark` explicitly in rabbitmq.conf to suit workload | Low | Config change |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Rollback Plan\n\nIf any phase fails:\n\n1. **Phase 1 (queue migration):** Re-declare `app-queue` as classic (`x-queue-type: classic`) and restore messages from backup. Producers/consumers must reconnect.\n2. **Phase 3 (config):** Revert the ConfigMap change and restart pods one at a time.\n3. **Phase 4 (3.12 → 3.13):** Patch the image tag back to `rabbitmq:3.12-management` and apply a full `partition=0` rollout. Quorum queues are backward-compatible.\n4. **Phase 5 (3.13 → 4.0):** Patch back to `rabbitmq:3.13-management` and roll back. Note: feature flags enabled in 4.0 cannot be disabled — rollback from 4.0 is not always possible if new flags were enabled; verify flag compatibility before proceeding.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Change Window Sizing Estimate\n\n| Phase | Estimated Duration |\n|---|---|\n| Phase 0 (Pre-check + backup) | 15–30 min |\n| Phase 1 (Queue migration) | 5–10 min |\n| Phase 2 (Policy) | 5 min |\n| Phase 3 (Config update) | 5 min |\n| Phase 4 (3.12 → 3.13 rolling) | 15–30 min |\n| Phase 5 (3.13 → 4.0 rolling) | 15–30 min |\n| Phase 6 (Validation) | 15 min |\n| **Total** | **~75–125 min** |\n\nPhases 1–3 can be done in a separate maintenance window ahead of the upgrade rollout if preferred.\n\n---\n\n*This document is a planning artifact. No changes have been applied to the cluster.*\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":497,"cache_read_input_tokens":34208,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":497},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b74bba5f-9368-4824-b7c5-9f0e8e404c5f","uuid":"a1c28555-e810-456c-a234-93e32fbf90f4","request_id":"req_011CcRKq5oi8jHxTQHe1msS4"}
